\f2 \uc0\u8232 
\fs48 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b\fs64 Precedence Effect
\f4 \uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0\fs36 a listener receiving the same sound from multiple sources locates it at the closest source, not at a point between them, unless the separation in time is less than about a millisecond - if the separation time is 35-50 msec, then a perceptible echo is heard - this means that the distance of the listener to each speaker must be precisely controlled in order to control localization effects.
\f2\fs48 \uc0\u8232 \u8232 
\f0\b\fs64 Synthetic Reverb
\f2\b0\fs48 \uc0\u8232 
\f1\fs36 combines EER and dense reverberation simulation circuitry: 
\f2 \uc0\u8232 \u8232 
\f0\b\fs64 FIR filter
\f2\b0\fs36 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 (tapped delay line) is used to synthesize early echo response (EER) the delays and gains of the taps are determined by the lengths and absorption of associated direct or reflective sound ray paths. The FIR output contains most of the directional and distance information for a virtual sound source.
\fs32 \
